  "prompt": "Does the law prohibit money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the law prohibits money laundering in virtually every country around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). It is a serious financial crime that is typically associated with other offenses such as drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud, and corruption.\n\n### Key Legal Frameworks:\n1. **International Standards**: \n   - The **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Its recommendations are adopted by many countries.\n   - The **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** and the **UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)** also address money laundering.\n\n2. **National Laws**:\n   - In the **United States**, the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **USA PATRIOT Act** are key laws targeting money laundering.\n   - The **European Union** has multiple Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Directives that member states must implement into national law.\n   - In **India**, the **Prevention of Money Laundering Act (PMLA), 2002** is the primary legislation.\n   - **China** has provisions in its **Criminal Law** and **Anti-Money Laundering Law** to combat this crime.\n\n### Prohibitions and Penalties:\n- Money laundering is a criminal offense punishable by fines, imprisonment, or both.\n- Financial institutions are required to implement robust AML programs, including customer due diligence (CDD), transaction monitoring, and reporting suspicious activities.\n\n### Enforcement:\n- Governments have dedicated agencies, such as the **Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)** in the U.S., the **National Crime Agency (NCA)** in the UK, and the **Financial Intelligence Unit (FIU)** in many countries, to enforce AML laws globally.\n- International cooperation is key, as money laundering often involves cross-border transactions.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is strictly prohibited by law, and violators face severe consequences. Governments and international organizations continue to strengthen regulations and enforcement mechanisms to combat this crime.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
